The {{ill|Shintai|ja|神体|1=Shintai|qq=draft|qq=draft}} is a single-wood-carved statue of {{ill|Ekādaśamukha|lt=Eleven-faced Kannon|ja|十一面観音|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, estimated to be from the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and standing 90 cm tall.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /> According to the ''{{ill|Shintōshū|ja|神道集|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'', the {{ill|Honji Suijaku|ja|本地仏|1=Honji_suijaku#Honji Buddha|lt=Honji Buddha|2=ja|3=本地垂迹|4=fr|5=Honji suijaku|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of Ikaho Shrine is an Eleven-faced Kannon, matching this description.

== History ==
=== Establishment ===
[[File:伊香保神社 Ikaho shrine - panoramio.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|{{ill|Ikaho Shrine|ja|伊香保神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Shibukawa, Gunma|ja|渋川市|qq=draft|qq=draft}})}}{{small|Located in the {{ill|Ikaho Onsen|ja|伊香保温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}} area, Sannomiya Shrine serves as its Satomiya.}}
The shrine is traditionally believed to have been established in {{ill|Tenpyō Shōhō|ja|天平勝宝|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 2 (750 CE), though detailed records are lacking.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" />

In medieval times, the ''Shintōshū'' describes the "Ikaho Daimyōjin" as having a female form enshrined at the Satomiya in Sannomiya Shibukawa, with its honji being the Eleven-faced Kannon. This suggests Sannomiya Shrine served as the Satomiya of {{ill|Ikaho Shrine|ja|伊香保神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Yuzen Shrine) in {{ill|Shibukawa, Gunma|ja|渋川市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref name=":1" /> 

